Warwickshire-based Silverstone Auctions has documented both the history of the car and the restoration process on a dedicated website.
It includes comments from Morecambe's chauffeur Mike Fountain, who sometimes drove the comedian and his wife Joan around in the Jensen.
However, as the car was marketed as a two-seater, there was little room for a third person. Mr Fountain said Morecambe often ended up "screwed up in the back".
The Jensen was, he said, Lancashire-born Morecambe's favourite car, however not everything about it pleased him.
In 1970 he wrote to the company's managing director to complain about the bodywork.
"Whilst bearing in mind that even the best chrome does not last for ever, the car has not had much use as the mileage is now only fourteen-and-a-half thousand miles and has always been kept in a garage.
"As for the paint work, I would refrain from comment, but would say that it is not what I expect of a £4,500 motor car," he wrote.
Jensen fixed the defects.
The car, which had been kept in the garage at the comedian's home in Harpenden, Hertfordshire, has now been extensively restored.
